MYOCARDITIS, RODENT VECTOR - SWEDEN (02)
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
Myocarditis, rodent vector - Sweden 980720235231
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 1998 10:01:00 -0400 (EDT)
From: Davis D. Janowski <Davis_Janowski@doh.state.fl.us>

Stepping back a bit from details of the virus and other related viruses to
possible means of exposure...
Being an avid backpacker, bushwacker and orienteer myself in the States, I
wonder if anyone has looked at the backwoods shelters/cabins these men (and
others) might have stayed in, especially on a following year around the
time of their exposure (rodents like to be warm and dry just like the rest
of us).
Also, it is common practice here in the States to drink water, albeit
filtered (using a backpacking pump/filter meant for that purpose), from
wild sources. Many viral contaminants are frequently too small to be
filtered by these units (especially if one removes or does not have one
that purports to be a "viral guard", which is prone to clogging by any
larger particulates).
--
Davis D. Janowski
Florida Epi Update Editor
Bureau of Epidemiology Publications Coordinator/Web Manager
e-mail: davis_janowski@doh.state.fl.us
Florida Department of Health
2020 Capital Circle SE, Bin #A-12
